[0m[49m[39m  166, 164[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  167, 165[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  168, 166[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  169, 167[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 170     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Runs association mining, sequential pattern mining, and statistical validation as Processing Jobs |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 171     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for diagnosis extracts, feature matrices, and pattern results |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Runs association mining, sequential pattern mining, community detection, and statistical validation as Processing Jobs (custom container with pre-installed dependencies) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for diagnosis extracts, feature matrices, pattern results, and Athena query results |
[0m[49m[39m  172, 170[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL for ICD-10 rollup, feature engineering, and patient-condition matrix construction |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 173     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Graph database for comorbidity network storage and community detection queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 174     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | Ad-hoc SQL queries over intermediate results in S3 |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 175     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Visualization dashboards for clinical stakeholder review |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Graph database for comorbidity network storage and interactive exploration queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | Ad-hoc SQL queries over intermediate results in S3 (dedicated workgroup with encrypted results bucket) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Enterprise edition visualization dashboards with row-level security for clinical stakeholder review |
[0m[49m[39m  176, 174[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing stores |
[0m[49m[39m  177, 175[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, job duration tracking, error alerting |
[0m[49m[39m  178, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 177[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  180, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  181, 179[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  182, 180[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  183, 181[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Diagnosis data extraction and ICD rollup.** The first step pulls longitudinal diagnosis data from the EHR extract and rolls granular ICD-10-CM codes up to a clinically meaningful grouping level. The choice of granularity is critical: too granular (full ICD-10) and you lack statistical power for combination analysis; too broad (major diagnostic categories) and you lose clinical specificity. Clinical Classifications Software Refined (CCSR) categories provide a good middle ground with ~530 categories, though many implementations use custom clinical groupers with 200-300 categories tuned to their population. The rollup also handles code versioning (ICD-10 codes change annually) and maps historical codes to current equivalents.
[0m[49m[39m  184, 182[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  185, 183[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  186, 184[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_and_rollup(population_criteria, lookback_years = 10):
[0m[49m[39m  187, 185[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull all diagnosis records for the target population.
[0m[49m[39m  188, 186[0m:[39m[49m     // Each record: patient_id, icd10_code, first_documented_date, encounter_type
[0m[49m[39m  189, 187[0m:[39m[49m     raw_diagnoses = query EHR extract where:
[0m[49m[39m  190, 188[0m:[39m[49m         patient meets population_criteria AND
[0m[49m[39m  191, 189[0m:[39m[49m         diagnosis_date >= (today - lookback_years)
[0m[49m[39m  192, 190[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  193, 191[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the ICD-10 to clinical grouper mapping.
[0m[49m[39m  194, 192[0m:[39m[49m     // This maps ~70,000 ICD-10 codes to ~300 clinical categories.
[0m[49m[39m  195, 193[0m:[39m[49m     // Example: E11.9 (Type 2 diabetes without complications) → "Diabetes mellitus"
[0m[49m[39m  196, 194[0m:[39m[49m     //          E11.65 (Type 2 diabetes with hyperglycemia) → "Diabetes mellitus"
[0m[49m[39m  197, 195[0m:[39m[49m     //          I50.9 (Heart failure, unspecified) → "Heart failure"
[0m[49m[39m  198, 196[0m:[39m[49m     grouper_map = load_clinical_grouper("ccsr_v2024")
[0m[49m[39m  199, 197[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 198[0m:[39m[49m     // Roll up each diagnosis to its clinical category.
[0m[49m[39m  201, 199[0m:[39m[49m     rolled_up = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  202, 200[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in raw_diagnoses:
[0m[49m[39m  203, 201[0m:[39m[49m         category = grouper_map.lookup(record.icd10_code)
[0m[49m[39m  204, 202[0m:[39m[49m         IF category is NULL:
[0m[49m[39m  205, 203[0m:[39m[49m             // Unmapped code. Log it for review but don't discard.
[0m[49m[39m  206, 204[0m:[39m[49m             log_unmapped_code(record.icd10_code)
[0m[49m[39m  207, 205[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[39m  208, 206[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  209, 207[0m:[39m[49m         append to rolled_up: {
[0m[49m[39m  210, 208[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:     record.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  211, 209[0m:[39m[49m             category:       category,
[0m[49m[39m  212, 210[0m:[39m[49m             first_date:     record.first_documented_date,
[0m[49m[39m  213, 211[0m:[39m[49m             encounter_type: record.encounter_type
[0m[49m[39m  214, 212[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  215, 213[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  216, 214[0m:[39m[49m     // Deduplicate: keep only the earliest occurrence of each category per patient.
[0m[49m[39m  217, 215[0m:[39m[49m     // A patient's "diabetes" entry should reflect when it was first documented,
[0m[49m[39m  218, 216[0m:[39m[49m     // not every subsequent encounter where it was carried forward.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 217[0m:[39m[49m     deduplicated = FOR each (patient_id, category) pair:
[0m[49m[39m  220, 218[0m:[39m[49m         keep the record with the earliest first_date
[0m[49m[39m  221, 219[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  222, 220[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN deduplicated
[0m[49m[39m  223, 221[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  224, 222[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 223[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Build patient-condition matrix and compute baselines.** Transform the longitudinal records into a binary patient-condition matrix (rows = patients, columns = condition categories, values = 0/1 presence). Also compute individual condition prevalences and expected pairwise co-occurrence rates under independence. These baselines are essential for calculating lift and identifying combinations that exceed chance expectations. Without this step, your pattern mining would surface obvious high-prevalence combinations (hypertension + hyperlipidemia) rather than genuinely surprising associations.
[0m[49m[39m  226, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 225[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  228, 226[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION build_matrix_and_baselines(rolled_up_diagnoses, min_prevalence = 0.01):
[0m[49m[39m  229, 227[0m:[39m[49m     // Construct binary patient-condition matrix.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 228[0m:[39m[49m     // Rows: patients. Columns: condition categories. Values: 0 or 1.
[0m[49m[39m  231, 229[0m:[39m[49m     patients = unique patient_ids from rolled_up_diagnoses
[0m[49m[39m  232, 230[0m:[39m[49m     categories = unique categories from rolled_up_diagnoses
[0m[49m[39m  233, 231[0m:[39m[49m     N = count of patients
[0m[49m[39m  234, 232[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  235, 233[0m:[39m[49m     matrix = zero matrix of shape (N, count of categories)
[0m[49m[39m  236, 234[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in rolled_up_diagnoses:
[0m[49m[39m  237, 235[0m:[39m[49m         row = index of record.patient_id in patients
[0m[49m[39m  238, 236[0m:[39m[49m         col = index of record.category in categories
[0m[49m[39m  239, 237[0m:[39m[49m         matrix[row][col] = 1
[0m[49m[39m  240, 238[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 239[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute individual prevalences.
[0m[49m[39m  242, 240[0m:[39m[49m     prevalences = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  243, 241[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each category in categories:
[0m[49m[39m  244, 242[0m:[39m[49m         col = index of category
[0m[49m[39m  245, 243[0m:[39m[49m         prevalences[category] = sum(matrix[:, col]) / N
[0m[49m[39m  246, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  247, 245[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter out rare conditions (below minimum prevalence threshold).
[0m[49m[39m  248, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Rare conditions produce unstable association metrics.
[0m[49m[39m  249, 247[0m:[39m[49m     active_categories = filter categories where prevalences[category] >= min_prevalence
[0m[49m[39m  250, 248[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  251, 249[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute expected pairwise co-occurrence under independence.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 250[0m:[39m[49m     // Expected P(A and B) = P(A) * P(B) if conditions are independent.
[0m[49m[39m  253, 251[0m:[39m[49m     expected_pairs = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  254, 252[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pair (cat_a, cat_b) in combinations(active_categories, 2):
[0m[49m[39m  255, 253[0m:[39m[49m         expected_pairs[(cat_a, cat_b)] = prevalences[cat_a] * prevalences[cat_b] * N
[0m[49m[39m  256, 254[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  257, 255[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN matrix, prevalences, expected_pairs, active_categories
[0m[49m[39m  258, 256[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  259, 257[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 260     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Association rule mining.** Apply the Apriori algorithm (or FP-Growth for better performance on large datasets) to find condition combinations with support above the minimum threshold. Then compute lift, confidence, and leverage for each discovered pattern. The minimum support threshold is a critical parameter: too low and you get millions of spurious patterns; too high and you miss clinically important but less common combinations. For a population of 200,000 patients, a minimum support of 0.5% (1,000 patients) is a reasonable starting point for pairwise patterns, with higher thresholds for three-way and four-way combinations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Association rule mining.** Apply FP-Growth to find condition combinations with support above the minimum threshold. Then compute lift, confidence, and leverage for each discovered pattern. FP-Growth is preferred over Apriori for this workload because it builds a compressed representation of the dataset (the FP-tree) that avoids repeated database scans. For 200,000 patients with 285 categories, the FP-tree fits comfortably in memory on an ml.m5.4xlarge instance (64 GB RAM). Apriori would also work at this scale but requires more passes over the data. The minimum support threshold is a critical parameter: too low and you get millions of spurious patterns; too high and you miss clinically important but less common combinations. For a population of 200,000 patients, a minimum support of 0.5% (1,000 patients) is a reasonable starting point for pairwise patterns, with higher thresholds for three-way and four-way combinations.
[0m[49m[39m  261, 259[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  262, 260[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  263, 261[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION mine_association_rules(matrix, prevalences, active_categories,
[0m[49m[39m  264, 262[0m:[39m[49m                                 min_support = 0.005, max_pattern_size = 4):
[0m[49m[39m  265, 263[0m:[39m[49m     N = number of rows in matrix
[0m[49m[39m  266, 264[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  267, 265[0m:[39m[49m     // Use FP-Growth algorithm for efficient frequent itemset mining.
[0m[49m[39m  268, 266[0m:[39m[49m     // FP-Growth avoids the candidate generation step of Apriori,
[0m[49m[39m  269, 267[0m:[39m[49m     // making it faster for large, dense datasets.
[0m[49m[39m  270, 268[0m:[39m[49m     frequent_itemsets = fp_growth(
[0m[49m[39m  271, 269[0m:[39m[49m         transaction_matrix = matrix (filtered to active_categories),
[0m[49m[39m  272, 270[0m:[39m[49m         min_support = min_support,
[0m[49m[39m  273, 271[0m:[39m[49m         max_itemset_size = max_pattern_size
[0m[49m[39m  274, 272[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  275, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  276, 274[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute association metrics for each frequent itemset.
[0m[49m[39m  277, 275[0m:[39m[49m     patterns = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  278, 276[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each itemset in frequent_itemsets:
[0m[49m[39m  279, 277[0m:[39m[49m         observed_support = count patients with ALL conditions in itemset / N
[0m[49m[39m  280, 278[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  281, 279[0m:[39m[49m         // Expected support under independence = product of individual prevalences
[0m[49m[39m  282, 280[0m:[39m[49m         expected_support = product of prevalences[cat] for cat in itemset
[0m[49m[39m  283, 281[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  284, 282[0m:[39m[49m         lift = observed_support / expected_support
[0m[49m[39m  285, 283[0m:[39m[49m         leverage = observed_support - expected_support
[0m[49m[39m  286, 284[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  287, 285[0m:[39m[49m         // Patient count for interpretability
[0m[49m[39m  288, 286[0m:[39m[49m         patient_count = observed_support * N
[0m[49m[39m  289, 287[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  290, 288[0m:[39m[49m         pattern = {
[0m[49m[39m  291, 289[0m:[39m[49m             conditions:       itemset,
[0m[49m[39m  292, 290[0m:[39m[49m             size:             count of conditions in itemset,
[0m[49m[39m  293, 291[0m:[39m[49m             support:          observed_support,
[0m[49m[39m  294, 292[0m:[39m[49m             patient_count:    patient_count,
[0m[49m[39m  295, 293[0m:[39m[49m             lift:             lift,
[0m[49m[39m  296, 294[0m:[39m[49m             leverage:         leverage,
[0m[49m[39m  297, 295[0m:[39m[49m             expected_support: expected_support
[0m[49m[39m  298, 296[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  299, 297[0m:[39m[49m         append pattern to patterns
[0m[49m[39m  300, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  301, 299[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort by lift descending (most surprising combinations first).
[0m[49m[39m  302, 300[0m:[39m[49m     sort patterns by lift descending
[0m[49m[39m  303, 301[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  304, 302[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN patterns
[0m[49m[39m  305, 303[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  306, 304[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  307, 305[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Temporal sequence analysis.** For the top candidate patterns from Step 3, analyze the temporal ordering of condition acquisition. This transforms static co-occurrence patterns into dynamic trajectories. For each multi-morbidity pattern, determine: which condition typically appears first? What's the median time between conditions? Is there a dominant ordering, or do patients arrive at the same combination via different paths? This temporal information is what makes patterns actionable for prevention: if condition A reliably precedes condition B by 3 years, you have a window for intervention.
[0m[49m[39m  308, 306[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 307[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  310, 308[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION analyze_temporal_sequences(top_patterns, rolled_up_diagnoses, min_patients = 100):
[0m[49m[39m  311, 309[0m:[39m[49m     temporal_results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  312, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 311[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pattern in top_patterns:
[0m[49m[39m  314, 312[0m:[39m[49m         conditions = pattern.conditions
[0m[49m[39m  315, 313[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 314[0m:[39m[49m         // Get all patients who have ALL conditions in this pattern.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 315[0m:[39m[49m         pattern_patients = find patients with all conditions in rolled_up_diagnoses
[0m[49m[39m  318, 316[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  319, 317[0m:[39m[49m         IF count of pattern_patients < min_patients:
[0m[49m[39m  320, 318[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // insufficient data for temporal analysis
[0m[49m[39m  321, 319[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  322, 320[0m:[39m[49m         // For each patient, extract the ordered sequence of condition onset dates.
[0m[49m[39m  323, 321[0m:[39m[49m         sequences = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  324, 322[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each patient in pattern_patients:
[0m[49m[39m  325, 323[0m:[39m[49m             patient_sequence = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  326, 324[0m:[39m[49m             FOR each condition in conditions:
[0m[49m[39m  327, 325[0m:[39m[49m                 onset_date = first_documented_date for (patient, condition)
[0m[49m[39m  328, 326[0m:[39m[49m                 append (condition, onset_date) to patient_sequence
[0m[49m[39m  329, 327[0m:[39m[49m             sort patient_sequence by onset_date ascending
[0m[49m[39m  330, 328[0m:[39m[49m             append patient_sequence to sequences
[0m[49m[39m  331, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  332, 330[0m:[39m[49m         // Identify the most common ordering (permutation).
[0m[49m[39m  333, 331[0m:[39m[49m         // Example: for {diabetes, CKD, heart failure}, the most common
[0m[49m[39m  334, 332[0m:[39m[49m         // ordering might be diabetes → CKD → heart failure (65% of patients).
[0m[49m[39m  335, 333[0m:[39m[49m         ordering_counts = count frequency of each unique ordering in sequences
[0m[49m[39m  336, 334[0m:[39m[49m         dominant_ordering = ordering with highest count
[0m[49m[39m  337, 335[0m:[39m[49m         dominant_fraction = max count / total sequences
[0m[49m[39m  338, 336[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  339, 337[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute median inter-condition intervals.
[0m[49m[39m  340, 338[0m:[39m[49m         intervals = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  341, 339[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each consecutive pair (cond_a, cond_b) in dominant_ordering:
[0m[49m[39m  342, 340[0m:[39m[49m             days_between = collect (date_b - date_a) for all patients following this ordering
[0m[49m[39m  343, 341[0m:[39m[49m             intervals[(cond_a, cond_b)] = {
[0m[49m[39m  344, 342[0m:[39m[49m                 median_days: median(days_between),
[0m[49m[39m  345, 343[0m:[39m[49m                 iqr_days:    interquartile_range(days_between)
[0m[49m[39m  346, 344[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  347, 345[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  348, 346[0m:[39m[49m         temporal_results.append({
[0m[49m[39m  349, 347[0m:[39m[49m             pattern:             pattern,
[0m[49m[39m  350, 348[0m:[39m[49m             dominant_ordering:   dominant_ordering,
[0m[49m[39m  351, 349[0m:[39m[49m             dominant_fraction:   dominant_fraction,
[0m[49m[39m  352, 350[0m:[39m[49m             intervals:           intervals,
[0m[49m[39m  353, 351[0m:[39m[49m             alternative_paths:   ordering_counts (excluding dominant)
[0m[49m[39m  354, 352[0m:[39m[49m         })
[0m[49m[39m  355, 353[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  356, 354[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN temporal_results
[0m[49m[39m  357, 355[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  358, 356[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 359     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 5: Network construction and community detection.** Build a comorbidity network where conditions are nodes and edges represent statistically significant co-occurrence (lift > threshold, FDR-corrected p-value < 0.05). Apply community detection to identify clusters of tightly connected conditions. These communities represent multi-morbidity "neighborhoods" that may share underlying mechanisms. Store the network in a graph database for interactive exploration and incremental updates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Network construction and community detection.** Build a comorbidity network where conditions are nodes and edges represent statistically significant co-occurrence (lift > threshold, FDR-corrected p-value < 0.05). Apply community detection to identify clusters of tightly connected conditions. These communities represent multi-morbidity "neighborhoods" that may share underlying mechanisms. Community detection (Louvain algorithm) runs in the SageMaker Processing Job using networkx or igraph after extracting the adjacency list. Results (community labels) are written back to Neptune as node properties for interactive exploration.
[0m[49m[39m  360, 358[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  361, 359[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  362, 360[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION build_comorbidity_network(patterns, prevalences, fdr_threshold = 0.05, min_lift = 1.5):
[0m[49m[39m  363, 361[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter to significant pairwise associations.
[0m[49m[39m  364, 362[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply chi-squared test for each pair and correct for multiple testing.
[0m[49m[39m  365, 363[0m:[39m[49m     pairwise_patterns = filter patterns where size = 2
[0m[49m[39m  366, 364[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  367, 365[0m:[39m[49m     p_values = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  368, 366[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pair in pairwise_patterns:
[0m[49m[39m  369, 367[0m:[39m[49m         // Chi-squared test of independence for this condition pair.
[0m[49m[39m  370, 368[0m:[39m[49m         chi2, p_value = chi_squared_test(pair.observed_support, pair.expected_support, N)
[0m[49m[39m  371, 369[0m:[39m[49m         pair.p_value = p_value
[0m[49m[39m  372, 370[0m:[39m[49m         append p_value to p_values
[0m[49m[39m  373, 371[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  374, 372[0m:[39m[49m     // Benjamini-Hochberg FDR correction.
[0m[49m[39m  375, 373[0m:[39m[49m     adjusted_p_values = benjamini_hochberg(p_values)
[0m[49m[39m  376, 374[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pair, adj_p in zip(pairwise_patterns, adjusted_p_values):
[0m[49m[39m  377, 375[0m:[39m[49m         pair.adjusted_p = adj_p
[0m[49m[39m  378, 376[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  379, 377[0m:[39m[49m     // Build network edges from significant, high-lift pairs.
[0m[49m[39m  380, 378[0m:[39m[49m     edges = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  381, 379[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pair in pairwise_patterns:
[0m[49m[39m  382, 380[0m:[39m[49m         IF pair.adjusted_p < fdr_threshold AND pair.lift >= min_lift:
[0m[49m[39m  383, 381[0m:[39m[49m             edge = {
[0m[49m[39m  384, 382[0m:[39m[49m                 source:    pair.conditions[0],
[0m[49m[39m  385, 383[0m:[39m[49m                 target:    pair.conditions[1],
[0m[49m[39m  386, 384[0m:[39m[49m                 weight:    pair.lift,
[0m[49m[39m  387, 385[0m:[39m[49m                 support:   pair.support,
[0m[49m[39m  388, 386[0m:[39m[49m                 p_value:   pair.adjusted_p
[0m[49m[39m  389, 387[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  390, 388[0m:[39m[49m             append edge to edges
[0m[49m[39m  391, 389[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  392, 390[0m:[39m[49m     // Construct graph and run community detection.
[0m[49m[39m  393, 391[0m:[39m[49m     graph = build_graph(nodes = active_categories, edges = edges)
[0m[49m[39m  394, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 393[0m:[39m[49m     // Louvain algorithm for community detection.
[0m[49m[39m  396, 394[0m:[39m[49m     // Finds groups of conditions that are more densely connected
[0m[49m[39m  397, 395[0m:[39m[49m     // to each other than to the rest of the network.
[0m[49m[39m  398, 396[0m:[39m[49m     communities = louvain_community_detection(graph, resolution = 1.0)
[0m[49m[39m  399, 397[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  400, 398[0m:[39m[49m     // Store in graph database for interactive exploration.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 399[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each node in graph.nodes:
[0m[49m[39m  402, 400[0m:[39m[49m         write_to_neptune(node, properties = {
[0m[49m[39m  403, 401[0m:[39m[49m             prevalence: prevalences[node],
[0m[49m[39m  404, 402[0m:[39m[49m             community:  communities[node]
[0m[49m[39m  405, 403[0m:[39m[49m         })
[0m[49m[39m  406, 404[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each edge in edges:
[0m[49m[39m  407, 405[0m:[39m[49m         write_to_neptune(edge)
[0m[49m[39m  408, 406[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  409, 407[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN graph, communities
[0m[49m[39m  410, 408[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  411, 409[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 412     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 6: Statistical validation and confounder adjustment.** Apply rigorous statistical filters to separate genuine multi-morbidity patterns from artifacts of age, sex, healthcare utilization, or multiple testing. This step is what separates research-grade discovery from noise. Patterns that survive validation are genuinely surprising given the population's demographics and utilization patterns. Patterns that don't survive were likely driven by confounders rather than true clinical associations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Statistical validation and confounder adjustment.** Apply rigorous statistical filters to separate genuine multi-morbidity patterns from artifacts of age, sex, healthcare utilization, or multiple testing. This step is what separates research-grade discovery from noise. Patterns that survive validation are genuinely surprising given the population's demographics and utilization patterns. Patterns that don't survive were likely driven by confounders rather than true clinical associations. Note: bootstrap resamples are computed in-memory and not persisted to disk. Ensure the SageMaker Processing Job uses an encrypted volume (configured via `ProcessingResources.ClusterConfig.VolumeKmsKeyId`) in case the algorithm spills to local storage during large-population resampling.
[0m[49m[39m  413, 411[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  414, 412[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  415, 413[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION validate_patterns(patterns, patient_demographics, min_lift_adjusted = 1.3):
[0m[49m[39m  416, 414[0m:[39m[49m     validated = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  417, 415[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  418, 416[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each pattern in patterns:
[0m[49m[39m  419, 417[0m:[39m[49m         // --- Age and sex adjustment ---
[0m[49m[39m  420, 418[0m:[39m[49m         // Stratify by age decade and sex. Recompute lift within each stratum.
[0m[49m[39m  421, 419[0m:[39m[49m         // If the pattern's lift drops below threshold after stratification,
[0m[49m[39m  422, 420[0m:[39m[49m         // it was driven by age/sex confounding, not a true clinical association.
[0m[49m[39m  423, 421[0m:[39m[49m         strata_lifts = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  424, 422[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each stratum in (age_decade x sex) combinations:
[0m[49m[39m  425, 423[0m:[39m[49m             stratum_patients = filter to patients in this stratum
[0m[49m[39m  426, 424[0m:[39m[49m             IF count of stratum_patients < 500:
[0m[49m[39m  427, 425[0m:[39m[49m                 CONTINUE  // insufficient power in this stratum
[0m[49m[39m  428, 426[0m:[39m[49m             stratum_lift = compute_lift(pattern.conditions, stratum_patients)
[0m[49m[39m  429, 427[0m:[39m[49m             append stratum_lift to strata_lifts
[0m[49m[39m  430, 428[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  431, 429[0m:[39m[49m         adjusted_lift = median(strata_lifts)
[0m[49m[39m  432, 430[0m:[39m[49m         IF adjusted_lift < min_lift_adjusted:
[0m[49m[39m  433, 431[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // pattern explained by demographics
[0m[49m[39m  434, 432[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  435, 433[0m:[39m[49m         // --- Utilization adjustment ---
[0m[49m[39m  436, 434[0m:[39m[49m         // Patients with more encounters get more diagnoses documented.
[0m[49m[39m  437, 435[0m:[39m[49m         // Check if the pattern persists after matching on encounter count.
[0m[49m[39m  438, 436[0m:[39m[49m         utilization_adjusted_lift = compute_lift_matched_on_utilization(
[0m[49m[39m  439, 437[0m:[39m[49m             pattern.conditions, patient_demographics
[0m[49m[39m  440, 438[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  441, 439[0m:[39m[49m         IF utilization_adjusted_lift < min_lift_adjusted:
[0m[49m[39m  442, 440[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // pattern explained by documentation intensity
[0m[49m[39m  443, 441[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  444, 442[0m:[39m[49m         // --- Bootstrap stability ---
[0m[49m[39m  445, 443[0m:[39m[49m         // Resample patients 100 times. Pattern must appear in >80% of resamples.
[0m[49m[39m  446, 444[0m:[39m[49m         stable_count = 0
[0m[49m[39m  447, 445[0m:[39m[49m         FOR i in 1 to 100:
[0m[49m[39m  448, 446[0m:[39m[49m             bootstrap_sample = resample patients with replacement
[0m[49m[39m  449, 447[0m:[39m[49m             bootstrap_lift = compute_lift(pattern.conditions, bootstrap_sample)
[0m[49m[39m  450, 448[0m:[39m[49m             IF bootstrap_lift >= min_lift_adjusted:
[0m[49m[39m  451, 449[0m:[39m[49m                 stable_count += 1
[0m[49m[39m  452, 450[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  453, 451[0m:[39m[49m         stability = stable_count / 100
[0m[49m[39m  454, 452[0m:[39m[49m         IF stability < 0.80:
[0m[49m[39m  455, 453[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // pattern is unstable
[0m[49m[39m  456, 454[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  457, 455[0m:[39m[49m         // Pattern survived all validation checks.
[0m[49m[39m  458, 456[0m:[39m[49m         pattern.adjusted_lift = adjusted_lift
[0m[49m[39m  459, 457[0m:[39m[49m         pattern.stability = stability
[0m[49m[39m  460, 458[0m:[39m[49m         append pattern to validated
[0m[49m[39m  461, 459[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  462, 460[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN validated
[0m[49m[39m  463, 461[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  464, 462[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  465, 463[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter06.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  466, 464[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  467, 465[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  468, 466[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  469, 467[0m:[39m[49m Sample output for a validated multi-morbidity pattern:
[0m[49m[39m  470, 468[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  471, 469[0m:[39m[49m ```json
